insert into policies.policies(title, short_description, long_description, category) values
  ('Adopt a Formal Modal Hierarchy','This rule puts people first. When the city designs a street, the safety of people walking and biking is decided on before the needs of cars. This means safer and more comfortable trips for cyclists.','Amend the Engineering Design Criteria and Zoning & Development Code to formally adopt and codify a modal hierarchy (e.g., Pedestrians > Bicyclists > Transit > Vehicles). This provides a non-negotiable framework for design trade-offs, ensuring that in constrained right-of-way scenarios, the safety and comfort of vulnerable road users are prioritized over vehicular Level of Service (LOS).','Design'),
  ('Mandate Target Speed Design','This tells city builders to design streets that make cars go slower on purpose. Instead of making wide, straight roads that feel like highways, they would build streets that naturally encourage slower driving. Slower cars mean much safer streets for everyone on a bike.','Revise the Engineering Design Criteria to shift from a reactive "design speed" methodology (accommodating the 85th percentile) to a proactive "target speed" approach. This requires using geometric design and traffic calming to engineer a desired, lower operating speed, fundamentally reducing crash probability and severity in line with Vision Zero principles.','Design'),
  ('Update Intersection Sight Distance Standards','This changes the rules for how far drivers need to see at corners. The old rules were just about cars seeing other cars. The new rules make sure drivers can see people on bikes and on foot, and that people can see cars. It helps prevent drivers from turning into cyclists they didn''t see.','Replace the current vehicle-centric Intersection Sight Distance standard with one based on NACTO guidance. The updated standard must be predicated on target speeds, not design speeds, analyze multi-modal sight triangles, and de-prioritize the removal of beneficial streetscape elements (e.g., shade trees) in favor of geometric or speed-based safety solutions.','Design'),
  ('Require Context-Sensitive Bicycle Facilities','This rule requires the best kind of bike lane for the street. On busy, fast streets, it means the city must build a protected bike lane with a barrier between bikes and cars. This provides the highest level of safety and makes cycling feel much more comfortable.','Amend the Engineering Design Criteria to mandate context-sensitive bicycle facilities based on a selection matrix (per NACTO/FHWA guidance) that uses traffic speed and volume as key inputs. This would require protected or buffered facilities on all arterial and collector streets unless specific, documented constraints are approved, moving beyond basic facility provision to guaranteed high-comfort infrastructure.','Design'),
  ('Strengthen Intersection Design Standards','This makes intersections safer for bikes. It includes making corners tighter so cars have to turn more slowly, and adding special waiting areas for bikes at the front of a traffic light (called "bike boxes") so they are more visible to drivers.','Mandate minimized corner radii to control vehicle turning speeds and reduce pedestrian crossing distances. Require the evaluation and implementation of bicycle-specific intersection treatments (e.g., bike boxes, two-stage turn queue boxes, protected intersections, dedicated bicycle signal phasing) based on established warrants.','Design'),
  ('Enhance Crossing Treatment Policies','This rule means the city has to use proven safety features at crosswalks, like special flashing lights (RRFBs) or raised crosswalks that act like speed bumps. It makes sure drivers see cyclists and pedestrians who are crossing the street.','Mandate specific, evidence-based crossing treatments (e.g., LPIs, RRFBs, PHBs, raised crosswalks, median refuge islands) based on established warrants related to street width, speed, volume, and demand. Require enhanced crosswalk illumination that meets IES RP-8 standards for nighttime visibility.','Design'),
  ('Improve Temporary Traffic Control Manual','This improves the rules for construction zones. It would add better instructions and pictures to show how to create safe pathways for bikes around construction, so cyclists don''t have to swerve into dangerous car traffic.','Update the Traffic Barricade Manual to provide more specific, detailed guidance and diagrams for preferred bicycle accommodation and detours, similar to the existing detail for pedestrians. Explicitly reference MUTCD Chapters 6D and 6F for technical grounding and include guidance on minimizing the duration of non-vehicular facility closures.','Design'),
  ('Upgrade Pedestrian Realm Standards','This makes sidewalks better and safer, which also helps cyclists. It requires wider sidewalks and a "buffer" space for things like trees and benches, which creates more separation from car traffic.','Increase minimum sidewalk widths in pedestrian-priority zones and mandate dedicated furnishing/landscape zones (e.g., 6-ft walk zone + 6-ft furnishing zone on arterials). Add standards for continuous shade canopy coverage to create a safer, more comfortable pedestrian environment that supports multi-modal trips.','Design'),
  ('Adopt a Formal Complete Streets Policy','This is a promise from the city that every time a street is built or fixed, it will be made safe for everyone—people walking, biking, taking the bus, or driving. It makes sure that bike safety isn''t forgotten in any project.','Enact a City Council Resolution to adopt a binding Complete Streets policy. This policy should mandate adherence to NACTO Urban Street Design Guide standards for all public and private projects in the right-of-way and establish a transparent, public process for justifying and documenting any exceptions.','Planning'),
  ('Establish a Publicly Searchable Design Database','This creates a public website where anyone can see the plans for street projects. If the city doesn''t follow its own safety rules for a project, it has to explain why on the website. This keeps the city accountable.','Create and maintain a public database of all street design projects, detailing adherence levels to NACTO guidelines and providing documented rationale for any exceptions. This serves as a critical tool for performance monitoring, transparency, and accountability as part of a Complete Streets policy implementation.','Planning'),
  ('Refine Transportation Impact Study (TIS) Requirements','When a new building is planned, this rule makes the builder study how it will affect bike and pedestrian safety, not just car traffic. This helps find and fix problems for cyclists before the building is even constructed.','Strengthen the TIS policy to require specific impact analysis on non-vehicular modes, including a multi-modal Level of Service (M-MLOS) analysis or equivalent bicycle/pedestrian LOS evaluation. This moves beyond simply inventorying existing facilities to analyzing the safety, comfort, and connectivity impacts of development-generated traffic on vulnerable road users.','Planning'),
  ('Mandate Systemic Safety Analysis','This policy makes the city look at all its road projects to find and fix risks for cyclists before crashes happen. It''s like a safety check-up for the street design, focusing on what could be dangerous for people on bikes.','Require that all significant roadway capital projects undergo a formal pedestrian and bicycle safety review or Road Safety Audit (RSA). This proactive, systemic approach focuses on identifying and mitigating underlying risk factors for vulnerable users, rather than reacting only to crash history.','Planning'),
  ('Develop an Explicit Project Prioritization Methodology','This creates a fair system for deciding which bike projects get built first. It would use a scorecard to give points for things like improving safety, connecting neighborhoods, and helping areas that need it most.','Formally document and adopt a data-driven project prioritization methodology for the Transportation Master Plan that clearly incorporates and weights factors such as safety (especially for vulnerable users), equity, multi-modal connectivity, and network completion when selecting projects for Capital Improvement Program (CIP) funding.','Planning'),
  ('Link Land Use Approvals to Bicycle-Friendly Design','This rule connects building permits to bike safety. For example, a new apartment building might get permission to be taller if its design makes it extra safe and easy for people to get to the sidewalk and bike lanes.','Amend the Zoning Code to explicitly link land use approvals or density allowances to the adoption of Transportation Demand Management (TDM) measures and the provision of high-quality pedestrian and bicycle access. Strengthen site design standards to prioritize building orientation and access points that enhance pedestrian safety and comfort.','Planning'),
  ('Establish a Tiered Bicycle Facility Maintenance Protocol','This is a plan to keep bike lanes clean and in good repair. It would set rules for how quickly the city has to fix potholes or sweep away glass and rocks from different types of bike lanes. This prevents crashes caused by bad road conditions.','Formalize an asset management protocol that classifies bicycle facilities into tiers and assigns corresponding service levels for routine and responsive maintenance (e.g., sweeping frequency, pavement repair timelines). This ensures that the significant capital investment in bicycle infrastructure is protected and that facilities remain safe and functional for users.','Maintenance'),
  ('Implement a Bicycle-Focused Pavement Condition Index (PCI)','This rule adds bike lanes to the city''s regular "road check-up" list. It makes sure that fixing a bad pothole in a bike lane is just as important as fixing one in a car lane. This means smoother and safer rides.','Integrate the condition of dedicated bicycle facilities into the city''s existing Pavement Condition Index (PCI) and asset management programs. This policy would mandate that pavement defects within a designated bike lane are scored and prioritized for repair with specific attention to bicycle safety and comfort impacts.','Maintenance'),
  ('Adopt Rapid Response Maintenance for Bicycle Facilities','This creates a faster system for fixing problems that make bike lanes unsafe, like debris or broken surface. It sets a target time (e.g., 48 hours) for the city to respond and communicate what was done.','Implement a rapid response protocol for bicycle facility hazards reported by the public (e.g., debris, potholes, damaged flex posts). This should include a service level agreement for response time (e.g., 48 hours to inspect and mitigate) and a public dashboard that transparently tracks response times and resolutions.','Maintenance'),
  ('Mandate Bicycle-Safe Utility Restoration Standards','This rule requires that when a utility company digs up a bike lane, they have to put it back as smooth and safe as it was before. No more rough patches or uneven seams that can cause crashes.','Update utility and encroachment permit conditions to require post-construction restoration that meets or exceeds pre-construction bicycle facility quality, including surface smoothness, slab joints, and flange gap standards. Include penalties and bonding requirements for deficient restoration.','Maintenance'),
  ('Require post-project bike safety audits','After a street project is done, this rule requires a bike safety check using real measurements and observations. If the street doesn''t meet the safety goals, fixes must be made.','Adopt a policy requiring post-implementation safety audits of projects that include bicycle facilities. Use objective measures such as operating speeds, conflict analyses, and user feedback to verify that the project achieves target safety outcomes; require corrective actions if outcomes are not met.','Maintenance'),
  ('Implement a Vision Zero framework with measurable goals','This is a citywide plan to eliminate severe injuries and deaths on the roads. It sets clear goals and tracks progress, focusing on protecting people biking and walking.','Adopt a Vision Zero policy with clear, time-bound goals and an implementation plan that focuses on reducing fatal and serious-injury crashes for vulnerable road users. Require annual public reporting on progress, including speed management and high-injury network mitigation.','Program'),
  ('Create a dedicated Bicycle Program Manager role','This hires a full-time city staff member whose job is to make biking safer and more convenient. They coordinate projects, policies, and funding to support cycling.','Create and fund a dedicated Bicycle Program Manager position within the Transportation Department. The role should oversee bicycle policy implementation, interdepartmental coordination, project delivery, and public engagement, ensuring sustained leadership and accountability for cycling improvements.','Program'),
  ('Implement a Road Diet Policy','This policy makes certain streets thinner for cars and wider for people. It reduces the number of car lanes and uses the space for bike lanes or center turn lanes, which makes cycling safer and reduces crashes for everyone.','Adopt a formal policy to implement road diets (lane reallocation) on multilane corridors where warranted by traffic volumes and safety considerations. Include warrants and guidelines for treatment selection (e.g., buffered or protected bike lanes) and commit to operational analyses that consider person-throughput and safety, not just vehicle Level of Service (LOS).','Program'),
  ('Adopt a Traffic Calming Program prioritizing high-injury corridors','This rule sets up a program to slow down cars in areas where there are lots of crashes, especially those that hurt people biking and walking. It uses tools like speed humps, curb extensions, or traffic circles to make streets safer.','Create a comprehensive Traffic Calming Program focused on high-injury corridors and areas with vulnerable users. Use proven measures such as speed cushions, raised crosswalks, curb extensions, and mini-roundabouts to reduce operating speeds and vehicle conflicts in priority areas, leveraging Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) proven safety countermeasures.','Program'),
  ('Create an annual Safe Streets Fund','This sets aside money every year to make streets safer for bikes and pedestrians. It dedicates a portion of the city''s budget to safety projects, so they don''t get delayed or ignored.','Establish a dedicated Safe Streets Fund that allocates a specified portion of the General Fund or other recurring revenue streams to bicycle and pedestrian safety improvements, including quick-build projects, maintenance, and permanent upgrades. Prioritize projects in equity-priority neighborhoods with documented safety needs.','Program'),
  ('Create a Neighborhood Slow Streets Program','This program slows down traffic in residential areas by creating calmer, safer streets for people walking and biking. It uses signs, street changes, and low-cost materials to reduce cut-through traffic and make neighborhood routes more comfortable.','Develop a Neighborhood Slow Streets program that designates low-traffic residential streets as bicycle-priority corridors. Use diverters, turn restrictions, traffic circles, and signage to discourage cut-through traffic and create connected, low-stress networks that complement major protected facilities.','Program'),
  ('Develop a Safe Routes to School (SRTS) Action Plan','This helps kids bike and walk to school safely by improving crosswalks, adding bike lanes, and educating families. It focuses on the routes children use every day.','Develop and implement a Safe Routes to School Action Plan in coordination with school districts, focusing on infrastructure improvements (e.g., protected crossings, traffic calming), education programs, and enforcement strategies near schools. Prioritize high-need schools based on safety data and equity indicators.','Education'),
  ('Establish a Driver Safety Education Campaign','This educates drivers about how to safely share the road with cyclists. It uses ads, workshops, and social media to teach drivers to slow down, yield, and avoid dangerous behaviors.','Launch a sustained public education campaign focused on driver behaviors that endanger bicyclists (e.g., speeding, failure to yield, unsafe passing). Include targeted enforcement in high-risk areas and incorporate messaging about the benefits of lower speeds and complete streets design.','Education'),
  ('Integrate Bicycle Education into Driver Licensing','This adds bike safety training into the process of getting a driver''s license. New drivers will learn about safe passing, dooring, and yielding to cyclists.','Advocate at the state level to incorporate bicycle safety education into driver licensing exams and periodic renewal processes. Include questions and educational materials on safe passing distances, dooring hazards, right-hook/left-hook scenarios, and yielding to bicyclists in bike lanes and at intersections.','Education'),
  ('Adopt a Parking Management Policy that Supports Cycling','This policy changes parking rules to support safer streets for cyclists. It might reduce minimum parking requirements and use the saved space for bike lanes or wider sidewalks.','Revise the parking code to reduce or eliminate minimum parking requirements near transit and in mixed-use areas. Implement dynamic curb management policies to reduce double-parking and dooring risk in bike lanes, and convert underutilized curb space to bike corrals and pedestrian amenities.','Planning'),
  ('Reform Speed Limit Setting Practices','This replaces the old way of setting speed limits (based only on how fast drivers go) with a safer method that considers the street''s design and the people using it.','Transition from the 85th percentile speed methodology to a Safe Systems approach that bases posted speed limits on street context, land use, and target operating speeds for vulnerable road user safety. Prioritize speed limit reductions on high-injury and school-zone corridors.','Enforcement'),
  ('Adopt Automated Speed Enforcement in School Zones','This uses cameras to catch drivers who speed in school zones. It helps slow cars down where kids are walking and biking.','Pursue enabling legislation (if needed) and implement automated speed enforcement in school zones and other sensitive areas. Pair with high-visibility signage and engineering changes to create self-enforcing slow-speed environments.','Enforcement'),
  ('Implement a Right-Turn-on-Red (RTOR) Reform Policy','This limits right turns on red lights at busy intersections or near bike lanes to reduce conflicts with people on bikes and on foot.','Adopt a policy to restrict or prohibit RTOR at intersections with high pedestrian and bicycle volumes, limited visibility, or documented crash history. Include warrants and a process for periodic evaluation and expansion.','Enforcement'),
  ('Adopt a Safe Passing Law with Local Enforcement','This helps protect cyclists by requiring drivers to give a safe distance when passing—usually at least 3 feet—and enforcing it with local tools.','Adopt and locally enforce a safe passing ordinance (e.g., 3 feet minimum) with targeted enforcement operations and public education. Equip officers with measurement devices and pair enforcement with public outreach on safe passing behavior.','Enforcement'),
  ('Create a Publicly Accessible Bicycle Crash Analysis Tool','This is a website where people can see where bike crashes happen and why. It helps the city find dangerous spots and fix them faster.','Develop a public-facing data portal that aggregates bicycle crash data, infrastructure attributes, and road conditions. Provide analytics and visualization tools for trend analysis, high-injury network identification, and near-miss reporting to inform safety interventions.','Data'),
  ('Enhance Bicycle Count Program with New Technology','This measures how many people are biking using better tools like automated counters and video analysis. It helps track progress and plan better bike projects.','Expand the bicycle count program by deploying permanent automated counters on key corridors and using computer vision techniques for periodic counts. Use the data to evaluate facility performance, estimate latent demand, and calibrate project prioritization models.','Data'),
  ('Establish an Open Data Standard for Bicycle Infrastructure','This standardizes how the city stores information about bike lanes and paths, so it''s easier to share with the public and use for planning.','Create and maintain an open, standardized geospatial dataset of bicycle facilities with attributes such as protection type, width, separation, and condition. Publish the data via an open data portal and require updates as part of project closeout processes.','Data'),
  ('Implement Incentives for Bicycle Commuting','This gives people rewards for biking to work, like cash, transit passes, or tax benefits. It encourages more people to ride instead of drive.','Establish a local incentive program for bicycle commuting, potentially in partnership with major employers. Offer incentives such as cash stipends, transit passes, or tax credits for employees who commute by bike, supported by employer-provided amenities like showers and secure bike parking.','Incentive'),
  ('Create a Bicycle-Friendly Business Certification','This gives awards to businesses that support cycling, like offering bike parking, discounts for cyclists, or safe delivery practices. It encourages more businesses to become bike-friendly.','Develop a certification program that recognizes businesses that adopt bicycle-friendly practices (e.g., secure bike parking, employee incentives, discounts for cyclists). Provide a public directory and marketing support to encourage participation and highlight best practices.','Incentive'),
  ('Adopt a Citywide Bicycle Parking Standard','This sets clear requirements for bike parking at new buildings and public spaces, so it''s safe, secure, and easy to use.','Amend the Zoning Code and development review standards to adopt clear quantitative and qualitative bicycle parking requirements, including minimum ratios, long-term/short-term space allocations, security standards, and design guidance for placement and access.','Design'),
  ('Implement a Low-Stress Bicycle Network Plan','This creates a connected network of safe, comfortable bike routes across the city using protected lanes, neighborhood greenways, and traffic-calmed streets.','Adopt a citywide Low-Stress Bicycle Network plan that prioritizes protected facilities on arterials, neighborhood slow streets on local roads, and safe crossings at major barriers. Use a network gap analysis to prioritize segments that deliver the greatest safety and connectivity benefits.','Planning'),
  ('Create a Bicycle Signal Policy','This adds special traffic signals for bikes at key intersections to reduce conflicts with turning cars and make cycling safer and more predictable.','Establish warrants and design standards for bicycle traffic signals, including leading bicycle intervals (LBI), protected bicycle signal phases, and two-stage turn boxes. Implement signals at high-conflict intersections and along protected lane corridors to improve safety and compliance.','Design'),
  ('Require Transparent Public Engagement for Street Projects','This requires city projects to include public input that specifically asks about bike safety and comfort, not just general feedback. It gives residents a voice in shaping safer streets.','Adopt a public engagement policy for street design projects that includes structured feedback on bicycle safety and comfort. Use standardized surveys, engagement dashboards, and clear communication about design trade-offs to ensure community-informed outcomes.','Program'),
  ('Publish an Annual Bicycle Report Card','This is a yearly report that shows how the city is doing on bike safety and network improvements, using clear data and goals.','Publish an annual Bicycle Report Card that tracks progress on safety metrics, network buildout, maintenance performance, and policy implementation. Use clear, accessible graphics and compare performance to peer cities to drive accountability and continuous improvement.','Program'),
  ('Require College Campus Bicycle Access Plans','This ensures that colleges have plans to make it safe and easy for students and staff to bike to and around campus.','Work with local universities and colleges to develop campus bicycle access plans that integrate with city networks, prioritize safe crossings at campus edges, and include on-campus infrastructure and education programs.','Planning'),
  ('Establish Safe Freight and Bicycle Interactions Policy','This reduces conflicts between large trucks and cyclists by setting specific rules and designs for streets where freight traffic and bike routes overlap.','Develop policies and design standards to safely manage interactions between freight vehicles and bicycle facilities, including dedicated freight routes, turning movement controls, and protected intersections. Prioritize safety in industrial areas and along corridors with significant truck traffic.','Planning'),
  ('Create Standard Operating Procedures for Temporary Bicycle Detours','This standardizes how to safely reroute bike traffic during construction or street closures, ensuring continuous protection and clear signage.','Develop SOPs for temporary bicycle detours that require equivalent or better protection during construction activities. Include clear signage, separation from traffic, and speed control measures. Hold contractors accountable through permit conditions and inspections.','Design'),
  ('Adopt a Protected Intersection Standard','This requires intersections to be designed so that bike lanes continue safely through the crossing, with physical protection from turning cars and clearer visibility.','Adopt a protected intersection design standard based on best practices from NACTO and peer cities. Apply the standard on all new or reconstructed arterial intersections along designated bicycle corridors, with context-sensitive variation as needed.','Design'),
  ('Create a Downtown Bicycle Network Plan','This creates a strong, low-stress network of protected bike lanes and safer crossings in the downtown area, where conflicts with cars and turning movements are common.','Develop a Downtown Bicycle Network Plan that designates a coherent, protected corridor network through the central business district. Address turning conflicts at high-volume intersections with signal phasing, protection, and corner geometry improvements.','Planning'),
  ('Adopt a Public Bike Parking Expansion Program','This expands secure, convenient public bike parking across the city, including on-street corrals, covered racks, and parking hubs near transit.','Create a plan and funding strategy to deploy public bicycle parking at high-demand locations, including on-street corrals, covered parking, and hubs near transit. Include design standards for security, weather protection, and ADA access.','Program'),
  ('Adopt an "Emergency Streets" Rapid Response Protocol','This rule treats a serious crash like the emergency it is. When someone is badly hurt or killed on a street, the city will immediately (within 7 days) put out temporary cones, signs, and barriers to slow down traffic at that spot. This makes the street safer right away and shows everyone that a safer design is possible, forcing the city to investigate how the street''s design may have caused the crash.','Formalize and adopt a pre-defined, quick-build response protocol for all crashes resulting in a Killed or Seriously Injured (KSI) outcome. The policy must empower a designated official to deploy a pre-approved kit of temporary traffic calming materials within a 7 day timeframe to immediately reduce kinetic energy at the high-risk location. This protocol will leverage statutory emergency powers to bypass standard design approval processes, shifting the post-crash focus from individual fault to a systemic investigation of design speed versus target speed.','Design')
